{
  "What is plasma?": "",
  "A very cold form of solid matter that exists only in space": "",
  "A state of matter made of ionized gas with free electrons": "",
  "A special type of liquid found only inside the human body": "",
  "A dense solid material used to build spacecraft heat shields": "",
  "Plasma is the fourth state of matter, consisting of ionized gas — atoms that have lost or gained electrons. It forms when gas is heated to extremely high temperatures.": "",
  "Which state of matter is the most common in the universe?": "",
  "Solid": "",
  "Liquid": "",
  "Gas": "",
  "Plasma": "",
  "Plasma is by far the most common state of matter in the universe. Stars, including our Sun, are made almost entirely of plasma, and stars make up the vast majority of visible matter.": "",
  "Which of the following is a natural example of plasma on Earth?": "",
  "A flowing river of fresh water": "",
  "A lightning bolt during a storm": "",
  "A block of ice in the freezer": "",
  "A cloud of steam above hot water": "",
  "Lightning is natural plasma on Earth. The extreme heat of a lightning bolt ionizes the air, creating a channel of plasma that glows brightly.": "",
  "How is plasma typically created from gas?": "",
  "By cooling the gas to very low temperatures in a lab": "",
  "By adding enough energy to ionize the gas particles": "",
  "By compressing the gas until it becomes a dense solid": "",
  "By dissolving the gas in water and stirring the mixture": "",
  "Plasma is created by adding large amounts of energy to a gas, usually through extreme heat or electrical discharge. This strips electrons from atoms, creating ionized gas.": "",
  "What is the main component of stars like our Sun?": "",
  "Liquid metal": "",
  "Solid rock material": "",
  "Superheated plasma": "",
  "Compressed regular gas": "",
  "Stars are made primarily of plasma. The extreme temperatures in stars (millions of degrees) ionize hydrogen and helium atoms, creating plasma.": "",
  "Which household item uses plasma to produce light?": "",
  "A standard incandescent light bulb": "",
  "A fluorescent tube or neon sign": "",
  "A regular candle with a wax wick": "",
  "A battery-powered LED flashlight": "",
  "Fluorescent lights and neon signs contain gas that becomes plasma when electricity passes through it. The excited atoms emit light as they return to their normal state.": "",
  "What makes plasma different from a regular gas?": "",
  "Plasma is colder and denser than a regular gas at all times": "",
  "Plasma contains ionized atoms and free-moving electrons in it": "",
  "Plasma particles are locked in fixed positions like a solid form": "",
  "Plasma does not take up any space inside a container at all": "",
  "While both are fluids without fixed shape, plasma differs from gas because its particles are ionized — atoms have lost electrons, creating a mix of positive ions and free electrons.": "",
  "Can plasma conduct electricity?": "",
  "No, only metals and liquids can conduct electricity at all": "",
  "Yes, because it contains free electrons and charged particles": "",
  "No, because plasma is a gas and no gas can conduct electricity": "",
  "Yes, but only when cooled to temperatures below freezing point": "",
  "Plasma can conduct electricity because it contains free electrons and positively charged ions that can carry electrical current. This is a key property that distinguishes it from ordinary gas.": "",
  "The aurora borealis (northern lights) is caused by what interacting with Earth's atmosphere?": "",
  "Moonlight reflecting off ice crystals in clouds in the atmosphere": "",
  "Charged particles from the Sun exciting atmospheric gas molecules": "",
  "Lightning storms occurring at very high altitudes in the atmosphere": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions sending glowing ash high up into the night sky": "",
  "The aurora borealis occurs when charged plasma particles from the Sun (solar wind) interact with gas molecules in Earth's upper atmosphere, causing them to glow.": "",
  "Which of these is NOT an example of plasma?": "",
  "The glowing gas inside a neon sign at a store": "",
  "A bolt of lightning striking during a thunderstorm": "",
  "Water vapor rising from a boiling pot on a stove": "",
  "The surface of the Sun where nuclear fusion occurs": "",
  "Water vapor (steam) is simply water in the gas state — its molecules are not ionized. Neon signs, lightning, and the Sun's surface all involve ionized gas, which is plasma.": "",
  "What is ionization?": "",
  "The process of an atom gaining or losing electrons to become charged": "",
  "The process of cooling a gas until it becomes a liquid substance": "",
  "The process of two atoms bonding together to form a new molecule": "",
  "The process of a solid melting and turning into a liquid substance": "",
  "Ionization is the process where atoms gain or lose electrons, becoming electrically charged particles called ions. This is what happens to gas atoms when plasma forms.": "",
  "What is an ion?": "",
  "A neutral atom that has an equal number of protons and electrons": "",
  "An atom or molecule that carries an electrical charge from electron gain or loss": "",
  "A type of chemical bond that forms between two metals in a compound": "",
  "A particle found only in the nucleus of atoms alongside the protons": "",
  "An ion is an atom or molecule that has gained or lost one or more electrons, giving it a positive or negative electrical charge. Plasma is full of ions and free electrons.": "",
  "What does 'electrically charged' mean?": "",
  "Having an unequal number of protons and electrons in a particle": "",
  "Having exactly the same number of protons and electrons overall": "",
  "Being able to produce light when heated to a high temperature": "",
  "Being magnetic and attracted to other metals in the environment": "",
  "An electrically charged particle has an unequal number of protons and electrons. Positive charge means more protons; negative charge means more electrons.": "",
  "What does 'state of matter' mean?": "",
  "The condition of a substance that determines how it appears on the outside": "",
  "A physical form of matter defined by particle arrangement and energy level": "",
  "The color and texture of a chemical substance when observed in a laboratory": "",
  "The amount of mass contained in a specific volume of a particular substance": "",
  "A state of matter is a distinct physical form — solid, liquid, gas, or plasma — defined by the arrangement of particles and their energy levels.": "",
  "What does 'solar wind' mean?": "",
  "Strong wind caused by uneven heating of Earth's surface by the Sun's light": "",
  "A stream of charged plasma particles released from the Sun's outer layer": "",
  "A large explosion on the Sun's surface that sends rocks flying into space": "",
  "The gravitational pull of the Sun on nearby planets in the solar system": "",
  "Solar wind is a continuous stream of charged particles (plasma) that flows outward from the Sun's corona. It interacts with Earth's magnetic field and creates auroras.": "",
  "What is an electron?": "",
  "A positively charged particle found in the nucleus of every atom": "",
  "A negatively charged particle that orbits the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "A neutral particle found alongside protons inside the nucleus area": "",
  "A particle that exists only in plasma and not in any other state form": "",
  "An electron is a negatively charged subatomic particle that orbits the nucleus of an atom. In plasma, electrons are stripped from atoms and move freely.": "",
  "What does 'fluorescent' mean?": "",
  "Able to absorb energy and re-emit it as visible light immediately": "",
  "Able to conduct heat very efficiently through a solid material": "",
  "Able to dissolve in water and form a clear transparent solution": "",
  "Able to resist changes in temperature when exposed to sunlight": "",
  "Fluorescent means a substance absorbs energy (like UV light or electricity) and re-emits it as visible light. Fluorescent tubes contain plasma that causes a coating to fluoresce.": "",
  "What does 'electromagnetic' mean?": "",
  "Relating to the interaction between electric and magnetic fields in nature": "",
  "Relating only to the magnetic properties of iron and steel metal objects": "",
  "Relating to the gravitational attraction between large masses like planets": "",
  "Relating to the movement of particles from high to low concentration areas": "",
  "Electromagnetic refers to phenomena involving both electric and magnetic fields. Plasma responds strongly to electromagnetic forces because it contains charged particles.": "",
  "What is a 'plasma ball' (the decorative science gadget)?": "",
  "A glass sphere containing noble gas that forms visible plasma filaments when electrified": "",
  "A rubber ball coated with a special paint that glows in the dark without any electricity": "",
  "A metal sphere that creates static electricity when you rub it with a cloth very quickly": "",
  "A glass sphere filled with colored liquid that changes color based on the room temperature": "",
  "A plasma ball is a sealed glass sphere filled with noble gases. A high-voltage electrode at the center ionizes the gas, creating colorful tendrils of plasma.": "",
  "What does 'corona' mean in the context of the Sun?": "",
  "The dense solid core found at the very center of the Sun made of iron": "",
  "The outermost layer of the Sun's atmosphere made of extremely hot plasma": "",
  "The dark spots that appear on the Sun's surface due to magnetic activity": "",
  "The process of nuclear fusion that powers the Sun and produces its light": "",
  "The corona is the Sun's outermost atmospheric layer, made of extremely hot plasma reaching millions of degrees. It is visible as a glowing halo during total solar eclipses.": "",
  "A student sees neon signs glowing different colors on a city street. What creates the glowing light in these signs?": "",
  "Colored paint on the inside of the glass tubes reflects ambient light outward": "",
  "Electricity ionizes the gas inside the tubes, creating plasma that emits light": "",
  "Tiny LED bulbs hidden inside the glass tubes produce the different colored light": "",
  "Chemical reactions between the glass and the air outside produce glowing light": "",
  "Neon signs work by passing electricity through gas (neon or other gases) sealed in glass tubes. The electricity ionizes the gas into plasma, which emits characteristic colored light.": "",
  "During a thunderstorm, a lightning bolt heats the air to about 30,000 degrees Celsius. What state of matter does the air in the bolt's path become?": "",
  "The air remains as a regular gas because air cannot change states at all": "",
  "The air becomes a superheated liquid that quickly cools back into a gas form": "",
  "The air becomes plasma because the extreme heat ionizes the gas molecules": "",
  "The air becomes a solid because extreme temperatures compress particles tightly": "",
  "The extreme temperature of lightning (about 30,000 degrees C) ionizes the air molecules, turning them into plasma. This is why lightning glows — the plasma emits light.": "",
  "A welder uses a plasma cutter to slice through thick metal. How can plasma cut through metal?": "",
  "The plasma is so cold that it freezes and shatters the metal on contact with it": "",
  "The plasma is extremely hot and melts the metal while blowing away molten material": "",
  "The plasma contains acid that dissolves the metal surface through chemical reactions": "",
  "The plasma uses magnetic force to pull the metal apart at the molecular level now": "",
  "Plasma cutters create an extremely hot jet of plasma (up to 25,000 degrees C) that melts through metal. A gas jet blows away the molten material, creating a clean cut.": "",
  "A student wonders why plasma TVs can display such vivid colors. How does a plasma TV produce its image?": "",
  "Tiny cells of gas are ionized into plasma, which causes phosphors to glow in colors": "",
  "A liquid crystal layer bends light from a backlight into different color wavelengths": "",
  "Millions of tiny LED lights behind the screen turn on and off to create the image": "",
  "A projector inside the TV shines colored light onto the back of the screen surface": "",
  "Plasma TVs contain millions of tiny cells filled with gas. Electricity ionizes the gas into plasma, which emits UV light that strikes phosphor coatings to produce red, green, and blue colors.": "",
  "Scientists are researching nuclear fusion as a future energy source. Why is plasma essential for fusion energy?": "",
  "Plasma can be cooled to absolute zero which is needed for fusion to work properly": "",
  "Fusion requires extremely hot ionized gas so that nuclei can collide and combine": "",
  "Plasma absorbs radiation that would otherwise be dangerous to the power plant staff": "",
  "Plasma is the only substance that can be stored in containers made of regular glass": "",
  "Nuclear fusion requires temperatures of millions of degrees to force atomic nuclei together. At these temperatures, matter exists as plasma. Containing this hot plasma is a major engineering challenge.": "",
  "Why does plasma respond to magnetic fields while regular gas does not?": "",
  "Plasma particles are heavier than gas particles and magnets pull heavy objects": "",
  "Plasma contains electrically charged particles that interact with magnetic fields": "",
  "Regular gas is too spread out for magnetic fields to have any effect on its particles": "",
  "Plasma has a fixed shape like a solid, so magnetic fields can grab onto it physically": "",
  "Plasma contains free electrons and ions (charged particles), which are affected by magnetic and electric fields. Regular gas has neutral atoms that do not interact with magnetic fields.": "",
  "A student visits a science museum and touches a plasma ball. The glowing filaments move toward their finger. Why?": "",
  "The glass becomes hot at the touch point and attracts the plasma filaments there": "",
  "The finger provides a grounding point and the charged plasma is attracted to it": "",
  "Static electricity from the finger repels the plasma toward other parts of the ball": "",
  "Body heat from the finger creates a convection current that pulls the filaments over": "",
  "Your finger acts as a conductive grounding point. The charged plasma particles are attracted toward your finger because it provides a path for electrical charges to flow.": "",
  "The Sun's corona has temperatures over 1 million degrees Celsius, much hotter than its surface. If you could somehow scoop up some corona plasma and bring it to Earth, would it feel extremely hot?": "",
  "Yes, it would instantly vaporize everything nearby because of its extreme temperature": "",
  "No, because the particles are so spread out there would be very little thermal energy": "",
  "Yes, because any plasma from the Sun is always dangerous regardless of its density": "",
  "No, because plasma cools down instantly to room temperature when removed from the Sun": "",
  "The corona's particles have extremely high individual temperatures, but they are spread so thinly that the total thermal energy in a small scoop would be tiny — not enough to feel very hot.": "",
  "A student asks: 'If a candle flame contains plasma, why can I put my hand near it without getting shocked?' What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Candle flames do not actually contain any plasma at all, only hot gas and soot": "",
  "The small amount of plasma in a flame is too weak and brief to cause an electric shock": "",
  "Human skin is completely immune to the effects of all forms of plasma in every case": "",
  "The oxygen in the air neutralizes all the electrical charge from the flame immediately": "",
  "A candle flame does contain a small amount of weakly ionized plasma, but the degree of ionization is very low and the energy is small, so there is no noticeable electric shock.": "",
  "Scientists use magnetic fields to contain plasma in fusion reactors. Why can't they just use a regular metal container?": "",
  "Metal containers are too expensive to build at the sizes needed for fusion reactors": "",
  "The plasma is so hot it would melt any known material, so magnetic fields confine it instead": "",
  "Metal blocks magnetic fields and plasma needs magnetic fields to survive and stay ionized": "",
  "Regular containers would make the plasma too cold and the fusion reaction would stop working": "",
  "Fusion plasma reaches temperatures of over 100 million degrees — far hotter than any material can withstand. Magnetic fields can confine the charged plasma without physical contact.": ""
}